article.headline: Mississippi St. 79, Arkansas 74
article.story:
NASHVILLE, Tenn. (AP) -- Tan White scored 22 points and Tiania
Burns added 21 to help Mississippi State beat Arkansas 79-74 in the
first round of the Southeastern Conference tournament Thursday.

The eighth-seeded Lady Bulldogs (14-14) advanced to play
top-ranked Tennessee in the quarterfinals on Friday.

The Lady Razorbacks (16-12), the No. 9 seed, trailed by 20 in
the opening minutes of the second half but whittled Mississippi
State's lead to two with 2:30 remaining.

Burns then scored at the other end, and SEC player of the year
Shameka Christon answered for Arkansas with a jumper to cut it to
71-73. Mississippi State had two straight baskets to go up by six.

Christon hit a 3 with 28.6 seconds, but it wasn't enough.
Doceide Warren sealed it for the Lady Bulldogs with two free
throws.

"I was pleased we found a way to win," Mississippi State coach
Sharon Fanning said. "(In the second half) I felt like we lost
focus and didn't play as hard together."

Mississippi State built an early lead, going ahead 28-15 after a
15-3 run with 9:17 to go in the first half.

Christon, who led the SEC in scoring with 21.9 points a game,
got two fouls and played only 12 minutes of the first half.

The Lady Bulldogs took advantage of her absence and stretched
the lead to 47-27 just before halftime.

"It wasn't clicking on offense. I thought it was important to
have (Christon) in the second half," Arkansas coach Susie Gardner
said about taking Christon out of the game.

Arkansas cut it to 11 early in the second half, but White
converted a three-point play at the other end to stop the spurt.

On the next play, White picked up her fourth foul and went to
the bench with 10:24 to go.

With White out, Arkansas finally got it down to seven after
Shanna Harmon's 3 and Kristen Moore's basket with 7:43 left.

White came back in. She picked up a loose ball and passed it up
to Burns for an easy layup that made it 71-60 with 4:30 to go.

Arkansas wouldn't go away and had a 9-0 run to pull within
71-69. But the Lady Razorbacks could never tie or take the lead.

"I thought definitely we were going to pull it out," Christon
said. "We were fighting, but it just didn't happen."

Mamie McKinney added 15 points for the Lady Bulldogs, who were
outrebounded 45-26 but scored 36 points off 22 Arkansas turnovers.

Christon had 20 points, 10 rebounds and a team-high six
turnovers in what could be her final game if the Lady Razorbacks
don't play in the WNIT.

Kristin Moore added 17 points and 12 rebounds and Kristin
Peoples had 10 points for Arkansas.

Ruby Vaden, who missed the Lady Razorbacks' final seven games of
the regular season with a stress fracture in her right foot, scored
four points in 11 minutes.
